result.execSummary:
Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Mary Jo C McMullen in court, in custody, with attorney Nicholas Martinez.   Bryan C. Bayer appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  The Court calls the matter to address the issue of the Defendant's competency.  The Defendant is mute on her response regarding competency. The State calls Dr. Rawski and he is sworn and testifies.  State moves for admission of Exhibit #3.  The Court accepts Exhibit #3 into evidence.   Dr. Rawski has determined that the Defendant is competent to stand trial. Cross examination by Attorney Martinez. Redirect by the State. The witness is excused.  The State rests.  The Defense calls Dr. Verwert and he is sworn and testifies.  Dr. Verwert has determined the Defendant is not competent to stand trial. Cross examination by the State.  Redirect by Attorney Martinez. The defense rests.    Closing statement made by the State.  Closing statement made by Attorney Martinez.  The Court finds the Defendant is competent to stand trial based on the testimony presented in Court. Attorney Bayer advises the Court that there is a possible new referral in their office.  Attorney Martinez requests the matter be set for plea and sentencing.  Plea/sentencing hearing scheduled for January 22, 2016 at 10:00 am.
